  "prompt": "Will our current scientific theories (especially evolutionary) be outdated in 100+ years?",
  "response": "It is difficult to predict with certainty the future status of current scientific theories. However, it is common for scientific theories to evolve over time as new discoveries are made and our understanding of the natural world grows.\n\nRegarding evolutionary theory, it has been remarkably robust and supported by a vast body of evidence since Charles Darwin and Alfred Russel Wallace first proposed the concept of natural selection in the 19th century. Over time, the theory of evolution has been refined and expanded with contributions from genetics, molecular biology, and paleontology, among other fields. It has adapted to new evidence and technological advancements, such as the discovery of DNA and the development of computational models.\n\nIn 100+ years, it is likely that evolutionary theory may continue to be refined and expanded as new evidence and methods are developed. Scientists will likely uncover more details about the mechanisms of evolution, the history of life, and the interplay of genetic, environmental, and epigenetic factors. However, the fundamental principles of evolution\u2014such as the concept of natural selection and common descent\u2014are unlikely to be completely overturned, given the extensive evidence supporting them.\n\nIn the broader context, scientific theories in general are subject to revision and refinement. Some theories may be replaced by more comprehensive models that better explain observed phenomena. Advances in technology, interdisciplinary research, and unforeseen discoveries will drive changes in scientific understanding. \n\nUltimately, the iterative nature of science means that while our current theories may be outdated in specific details, they contribute to the foundation upon which future knowledge is built.",
